// Regression test for a known compiler bug, related to (but distinct
// from) zero_arg_constructor_bare_call_error.fire: constructing an
// instance of a class *imported from another module* via the bare
// `ClassName(args)` form (any arg count -- this reproduces with a real
// constructor argument, ruling out the zero-arg-specific bug in the
// sibling file) type-checks fine at the construction site, but the
// resulting variable's type isn't correctly registered for a later raw
// field access on it:
//   Field access on non-class type 'Widget'
// Calling a *method* on the same instance works fine -- this is
// specific to raw external field access after a cross-module bare
// construction. Discovered while designing
// @firescript/std.text.StringBuilder; worked around by never exposing
// raw field access from outside the class (all state goes through
// methods, which was already the right API shape regardless).
//
// (widget_helper.fire, the sibling module this test imports, exists
// solely to exercise this cross-module path.)
//
// Expected (correct) behavior once fixed: prints 7.
import @firescript/std.io.println;
import widget_helper.Widget;

w: Widget = Widget(7);
println(w.val);
